\doxysubsection{详细描述}
\doxylink{namespace_e_a}{EA} Standard Template Library 

NOTE\+:

All of the actual implementation is done via the ATOMIC\+\_\+\+MACROS in the compiler or arch sub folders. The C++ code is merely boilerplate around these macros that actually implement the atomic operations. The C++ boilerplate is also hidden behind macros. This may seem more complicated but this is all meant to reduce copy-\/pasting and to ensure all operations all end up going down to one macro that does the actual implementation. The reduced code duplication makes it easier to verify the implementation and reason about it. Ensures we do not have to re-\/implement the same code for compilers that do not support generic builtins such as MSVC. Ensures for compilers that have separate intrinsics for different widths, that C++ boilerplate isn\textquotesingle{}t copy-\/pasted leading to programmer errors. Ensures if we ever have to implement a new platform, only the low-\/level leaf macros have to be implemented, everything else will be generated for you.

\doxylink{structeastl_1_1aligned__buffer}{aligned\+\_\+buffer}

This is useful for creating a buffer of the same size and alignment of a given struct or class. This is useful for creating memory pools that support both size and alignment requirements of stored objects but without wasting space in over-\/allocating.

Note that we implement this via struct specializations, as some compilers such as VC++ do not support specification of alignments in any way other than via an integral constant.

Example usage\+: struct Widget\{ \}; // This class has a given size and alignment.

Declare a char buffer of equal size and alignment to Widget. \doxylink{structeastl_1_1aligned__buffer}{aligned\+\_\+buffer$<$sizeof(\+Widget), EASTL\+\_\+\+ALIGN\+\_\+\+OF(\+Widget)$>$} m\+Widget\+Buffer;

\doxylink{namespaceeastl_ab6ed782d6695cb01fb7889ea6d7b46aa}{fixed\+\_\+ring\+\_\+buffer}

This is a convenience template alias for creating a fixed-\/sized \doxylink{classeastl_1_1ring__buffer}{ring\+\_\+buffer} using \doxylink{classeastl_1_1fixed__vector}{eastl\+::fixed\+\_\+vector} as its storage container. This has been tricky for users to get correct due to the constructor requirements of \doxylink{classeastl_1_1ring__buffer}{eastl\+::ring\+\_\+buffer} leaking the implementation detail of the sentinel value being used internally. In addition, it was not obvious what the correct allocator\+\_\+type template parameter should be used for containers providing both a default allocator type and an overflow allocator type.

We are over-\/allocating the \doxylink{classeastl_1_1fixed__vector}{fixed\+\_\+vector} container to accommodate the \doxylink{classeastl_1_1ring__buffer}{ring\+\_\+buffer} sentinel to prevent that implementation detail leaking into user code.

Example usage\+: \begin{DoxyVerb}fixed_ring_buffer<int, 8> rb = {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7};
\end{DoxyVerb}
 or \doxylink{namespaceeastl_ab6ed782d6695cb01fb7889ea6d7b46aa}{fixed\+\_\+ring\+\_\+buffer$<$int, 8$>$} rb(8); // capacity doesn\textquotesingle{}t need to respect sentinel rb.\+push\+\_\+back(0); \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a9a656fdd506971e09dc8613ed92c15d7}\index{eastl@{eastl}!giga@{giga}}

\doxylink{namespaceeastl_a84f33f71b40540213361b6dce7f22114}{iterator\+\_\+status\+\_\+flag}

Defines the validity status of an iterator. This is primarily used for iterator validation in debug builds. These are implemented as OR-\/able flags (as opposed to mutually exclusive values) in order to deal with the nature of iterator status. In particular, an iterator may be valid but not dereferencable, as in the case with an iterator to container \doxylink{namespaceeastl_a015a7329c4b84d454b87496532739b69}{end()}. An iterator may be valid but also dereferencable, as in the case with an iterator to container \doxylink{namespaceeastl_a5416077556bbc43ecf1cdbab7b44c386}{begin()}. \begin{DoxyEnumFields}[2]{枚举值}

adjust\+\_\+heap

Given a position that has just been vacated, this function moves new values into that vacated position appropriately. The value argument is an entry which will be inserted into the heap after we move nodes into the positions that were vacated.

align

Same as C++11 std\+::align. \href{http://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/memory/align}{\texttt{ http\+://en.\+cppreference.\+com/w/cpp/memory/align}} If it is possible to fit size bytes of storage aligned by alignment into the buffer pointed to by ptr with length space, the function updates ptr to point to the first possible address of such storage, decreases space by the number of bytes used for alignment, and returns the new ptr value. Otherwise, the function returns NULL and leaves ptr and space unmodified.

Example usage\+: char buffer\mbox{[}512\mbox{]}; size\+\_\+t space = sizeof(buffer); void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p = buffer; void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p1 = eastl\+::align(16,  3, p, space); p = (char\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*})p + 3; space -\/= 3; void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p2 = eastl\+::align(32, 78, p, space); p = (char\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*})p + 78; space -\/= 78; void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p3 = eastl\+::align(64,  9, p, space); p = (char\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*})p + 9; space -\/= 9; 函数调用图\+:

align\+\_\+advance

Same as align except ptr and space can be adjusted to reflect remaining space. Not present in the C++ Standard. Note that the example code here is similar to align but simpler.

Example usage\+: char buffer\mbox{[}512\mbox{]}; size\+\_\+t space = sizeof(buffer); void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p = buffer; void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p1 = eastl\+::align\+\_\+advance(16,  3, p, space, \&p, \&space); // p is advanced and space reduced accordingly. void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p2 = eastl\+::align\+\_\+advance(32, 78, p, space, \&p, \&space); void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p3 = eastl\+::align\+\_\+advance(64,  9, p, space, \&p, \&space); void\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p4 = eastl\+::align\+\_\+advance(16, 33, p, space); 函数调用图\+:

Forward\+Iterator eastl\+::apply\+\_\+and\+\_\+remove (\begin{DoxyParamCaption}\item[{Forward\+Iterator}]{first}{, }\item[{Forward\+Iterator}]{last}{, }\item[{Function}]{function}{, }\item[{const T \&}]{value}{}\end{DoxyParamCaption})\hspace{0.3cm}{\ttfamily [inline]}}

apply\+\_\+and\+\_\+remove

Calls the Function function for all elements referred to my iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding condition holds\+: value == \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i and then left shift moves potential non-\/matching elements over it.

Returns\+: a past-\/the-\/end iterator for the new end of the range.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding equality test
\begin{DoxyItemize}
\item applies function once for every time the condition holds.
\end{DoxyItemize}

Note\+: Since removing is done by shifting (by means of copy move assignment) the elements in the range in such a way that the elements that are not to be removed appear in the beginning of the range doesn\textquotesingle{}t actually remove it from the given container, the user must call the container erase function if the user wants to erase the element from the container. I.\+e. in the same they as for remove\+\_\+if the excess elements are left in a valid but possibly moved from state. 函数调用图\+:

Returns\+: a past-\/the-\/end iterator for the new end of the range.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate + applies function once for every time the condition holds.

Note\+: Since removing is done by shifting (by means of copy move assignment) the elements in the range in such a way that the elements that are not to be removed appear in the beginning of the range doesn\textquotesingle{}t actually remove it from the given container, the user must call the container erase function if the user wants to erase the element from the container. binary\+\_\+search

Returns\+: true if there is an iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first last) that satisfies the corresponding conditions\+: !(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} value) \&\& !(value \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i).

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}log(last -\/ first) + 2\textquotesingle{} comparisons.

Note\+: The reason binary\+\_\+search returns bool instead of an iterator is that search\+\_\+n, lower\+\_\+bound, or equal\+\_\+range already return an iterator. However, there are arguments that binary\+\_\+search should return an iterator. Note that we provide binary\+\_\+search\+\_\+i (STL extension) to return an iterator.

To use search\+\_\+n to find an item, do this\+: iterator i = search\+\_\+n(begin, end, 1, value); To use lower\+\_\+bound to find an item, do this\+: iterator i = lower\+\_\+bound(begin, end, value); if((i != last) \&\& !(value \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i)) $<$use the iterator$>$ It turns out that the above lower\+\_\+bound method is as fast as binary\+\_\+search would be if it returned an iterator. 函数调用图\+:

comb\+\_\+sort

This is an unstable sort. Implements the Comb\+Sort algorithm; in particular, implements the Comb\+Sort11 variation of the Comb\+Sort algorithm, based on the reference to \textquotesingle{}11\textquotesingle{} in the implementation.

To consider\+: Use a comb sort table instead of the \textquotesingle{}((n\+Space \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} 10) + 3) / 13\textquotesingle{} expression. Ideal tables can be found on the Internet by looking up "{}comb sort table"{}. 函数调用图\+:

template$<$typename Input\+Iterator, typename Output\+Iterator$>$ \\
Output\+Iterator eastl\+::copy (\begin{DoxyParamCaption}\item[{Input\+Iterator}]{first}{, }\item[{Input\+Iterator}]{last}{, }\item[{Output\+Iterator}]{result}{}\end{DoxyParamCaption})\hspace{0.3cm}{\ttfamily [inline]}}

copy

Effects\+: Copies elements in the range \mbox{[}first, last) into the range \mbox{[}result, result + (last -\/ first)) starting from first and proceeding to last. For each nonnegative integer n \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} (last -\/ first), performs \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(result + n) = \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first + n).

Returns\+: result + (last -\/ first). That is, returns the end of the result. Note that this is different from how memmove/memcpy work, as they return the beginning of the result.

Requires\+: result shall not be in the range \mbox{[}first, last). But the end of the result range may in fact be within the input rante.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} assignments. 函数调用图\+:

copy\+\_\+backward

copies memory in the range of \mbox{[}first, last) to the range {\itshape ending} with result.

Effects\+: Copies elements in the range \mbox{[}first, last) into the range \mbox{[}result -\/ (last -\/ first), result) starting from last 1 and proceeding to first. For each positive integer n \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}= (last -\/ first), performs \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(result n) = \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(last -\/ n).

Requires\+: result shall not be in the range \mbox{[}first, last).

Returns\+: result -\/ (last -\/ first). That is, returns the beginning of the result range.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} assignments. 函数调用图\+:

count

Counts the number of items in the range of \mbox{[}first, last) which equal the input value.

Effects\+: Returns the number of iterators i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding conditions hold\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i == value.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate.

Note\+: The predicate version of count is count\+\_\+if and not another variation of count. This is because both versions would have three parameters and there could be ambiguity. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a87b519bb89836d1146543292914c55ff}\index{eastl@{eastl}!count@{count}}

count\+\_\+if

Counts the number of items in the range of \mbox{[}first, last) which match the input value as defined by the input predicate function.

Effects\+: Returns the number of iterators i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding conditions hold\+: predicate(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i) != false.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate.

Note\+: The non-\/predicate version of count\+\_\+if is count and not another variation of count\+\_\+if. This is because both versions would have three parameters and there could be ambiguity. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a2b93b98755a5b22efe65dbf0cb6f4f99}\index{eastl@{eastl}!cp\_swap@{cp\_swap}}

ht\+\_\+distance

This function returns the same thing as \doxylink{namespaceeastl_ab917da722315c1690092f5014763fa32}{distance()} for forward iterators but returns zero for input iterators. The reason why is that input iterators can only be read once, and calling \doxylink{namespaceeastl_ab917da722315c1690092f5014763fa32}{distance()} on an input iterator destroys the ability to read it. This ht\+\_\+distance is used only for optimization and so the code will merely work better with forward iterators that input iterators. 函数调用图\+:

equal

Returns\+: true if for every iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) the following corresponding conditions hold\+: predicate(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i, \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first2 + (i -\/ first1))) != false. Otherwise, returns false.

Complexity\+: At most last1 first1 applications of the corresponding predicate.

To consider\+: Make specializations of this for scalar types and random access iterators that uses memcmp or some trick memory comparison function. We should verify that such a thing results in an improvement. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_af0bc1c10cc7e3db40caf12256ac4db84}\index{eastl@{eastl}!equal@{equal}}

equal\+\_\+range

Effects\+: Finds the largest subrange \mbox{[}i, j) such that the value can be inserted at any iterator k in it without violating the ordering. k satisfies the corresponding conditions\+: !(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}k \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} value) \&\& !(value \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}k).

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}2 \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} log(last -\/ first) + 1\textquotesingle{} comparisons. 函数调用图\+:

fill

fill is like memset in that it assigns a single value repeatedly to a destination range. It allows for any type of iterator (not just an array) and the source value can be any type, not just a byte. Note that the source value (which is a reference) can come from within the destination range.

Effects\+: Assigns value through all the iterators in the range \mbox{[}first, last).

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} assignments.

Note\+: The C++ standard doesn\textquotesingle{}t specify anything about the value parameter coming from within the first-\/last range. All std STL implementations act as if the standard specifies that value must not come from within this range. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a834fdf148dd6bd0e03e551e6a23ea583}\index{eastl@{eastl}!fill@{fill}}

find

finds the value within the unsorted range of \mbox{[}first, last).

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding conditions hold\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i == value. Returns last if no such iterator is found.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate. This is a linear search and not a binary one.

Note\+: The predicate version of find is find\+\_\+if and not another variation of find. This is because both versions would have three parameters and there could be ambiguity. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_af00673a05d4993debd8ad946516a92f3}\index{eastl@{eastl}!find@{find}}

find\+\_\+end

Finds the last occurrence of the second sequence in the first sequence. As such, this function is much like the C string function strrstr and it is also the same as a reversed version of \textquotesingle{}search\textquotesingle{}. It is called find\+\_\+end instead of the possibly more consistent search\+\_\+end simply because the C++ standard algorithms have such naming.

Returns an iterator between first1 and last1 if the sequence is found. returns last1 (the end of the first seqence) if the sequence is not found. 函数调用图\+:

find\+\_\+end

Effects\+: Finds a subsequence of equal values in a sequence.

Returns\+: The last iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1 -\/ (last2 -\/ first2)) such that for any nonnegative integer n \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} (last2 -\/ first2), the following corresponding conditions hold\+: pred({\itshape (i+n),}(first2+n)) != false. Returns last1 if no such iterator is found.

Complexity\+: At most (last2 -\/ first2) \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} (last1 -\/ first1 -\/ (last2 -\/ first2) + 1) applications of the corresponding predicate. 函数调用图\+:

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) such that for some integer j in the range \mbox{[}first2, last2) the following conditions hold\+: pred(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i, \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j) == false. Returns last1 if no such iterator is found.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}(last1 -\/ first1) \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} (last2 -\/ first2)\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate. 函数调用图\+:

find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of

find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of is similar to find in that it performs linear search through a range of Forward\+Iterators. The difference is that while find searches for one particular value, find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of searches for any of several values. Specifically, find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of searches for the first occurrance in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) of any of the elements in \mbox{[}first2, last2). This function is thus similar to the strpbrk standard C string function. If the sequence of elements to search for (i.\+e. first2-\/last2) is empty, the find always fails and last1 will be returned.

Effects\+: Finds an element that matches one of a set of values.

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) such that for some integer j in the range \mbox{[}first2, last2) the following conditions hold\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i == \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j. Returns last1 if no such iterator is found.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}(last1 -\/ first1) \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} (last2 -\/ first2)\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a7e59bf262e954a5867f6fc24f30c520c}\index{eastl@{eastl}!find\_first\_of@{find\_first\_of}}

find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of is similar to find in that it performs linear search through a range of Forward\+Iterators. The difference is that while find searches for one particular value, find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of searches for any of several values. Specifically, find\+\_\+first\+\_\+of searches for the first occurrance in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) of any of the elements in \mbox{[}first2, last2). This function is thus similar to the strpbrk standard C string function.

Effects\+: Finds an element that matches one of a set of values.

find\+\_\+if

finds the value within the unsorted range of \mbox{[}first, last).

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding conditions hold\+: pred(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i) != false. Returns last if no such iterator is found. If the sequence of elements to search for (i.\+e. first2 -\/ last2) is empty, the find always fails and last1 will be returned.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate.

Note\+: The non-\/predicate version of find\+\_\+if is find and not another variation of find\+\_\+if. for\+\_\+each

Calls the Function function for each value in the range \mbox{[}first, last). Function takes a single parameter\+: the current value.

Effects\+: Applies function to the result of dereferencing every iterator in the range \mbox{[}first, last), starting from first and proceeding to last 1.

Returns\+: function.

Complexity\+: Applies function exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} times.

Note\+: If function returns a result, the result is ignored. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a8574b1d19370c44341afad62ac61e60f}\index{eastl@{eastl}!for\_each\_n@{for\_each\_n}}

get\+\_\+default\+\_\+allocator

This templated function allows the user to implement a default allocator retrieval function that any part of EASTL can use. EASTL containers take an Allocator parameter which identifies an Allocator class to use. But different kinds of allocators have different mechanisms for retrieving a default allocator instance, and some don\textquotesingle{}t even intrinsically support such functionality. The user can override this get\+\_\+default\+\_\+allocator function in order to provide the glue between EASTL and whatever their system\textquotesingle{}s default allocator happens to be.

Example usage\+: My\+Allocator\+Type\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} gp\+System\+Allocator;

My\+Allocator\+Type\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} get\+\_\+default\+\_\+allocator(const My\+Allocator\+Type\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}) \{ return gp\+System\+Allocator; \} \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a231d8d3f43ae4ecaa1f85c48f8691f7a}\index{eastl@{eastl}!get\_default\_allocator@{get\_default\_allocator}}

hashtable\+\_\+find

Helper function that defaults to using hash\uline{ and \doxylink{structeastl_1_1equal__to}{equal\+\_\+to$<$$>$}. This makes it so that by default you don\textquotesingle{}t need to provide these. Note that the default hash functions may not be what you want, though.}

\uline{Example usage. Instead of this\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1hash__set}{hash\+\_\+set$<$string$>$} hash\+Set; hash\+Set.\+find("{}hello"{}, hash$<$char\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}$>$(), equal\+\_\+to$<$$>$());}

\uline{You can use this\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1hash__set}{hash\+\_\+set$<$string$>$} hash\+Set; hashtable\+\_\+find(hash\+Set, "{}hello"{}); }\Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a8c5cfb41214176a0f73eaf22cc2a2f26}\index{eastl@{eastl}!heap\_sort@{heap\_sort}}

identical

Returns true if the two input ranges are equivalent. There is a subtle difference between this algorithm and the \textquotesingle{}equal\textquotesingle{} algorithm. The equal algorithm assumes the two ranges are of equal length. This algorithm efficiently compares two ranges for both length equality and for element equality. There is no other standard algorithm that can do this.

Returns\+: true if the sequence of elements defined by the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) is of the same length as the sequence of elements defined by the range of \mbox{[}first2, last2) and if the elements in these ranges are equal as per the equal algorithm.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}min((last1 -\/ first1), (last2 -\/ first2))\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding comparison. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a754a7529e53dee28ff90e2fb605736fd}\index{eastl@{eastl}!identical@{identical}}

insertion\+\_\+sort

insertion\+\_\+sort is an O(n\texorpdfstring{$^\wedge$}{\string^}2) stable sorting algorithm that starts at the (k + 1) element and assumes the first (k) elements are sorted. Then copy\+\_\+backwards from (k + 1) to the begining any elements where the (k + 1) element is less than \mbox{[}0, k\mbox{]} elements. The position of k when (k + 1) element is not less than k is the sorted position of the (k + 1) element.

Example With Intermediate Steps\+: (k + 1) == 2 \+: \mbox{[}3, 2, 1\mbox{]} -\/\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} \mbox{[}3, 3, 1\mbox{]} -\/\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} \mbox{[}2, 3, 1\mbox{]} (k + 1) == 1 \+: \mbox{[}2, 3, 1\mbox{]} -\/\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} \mbox{[}2, 3, 3\mbox{]} -\/\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} \mbox{[}2, 2, 3\mbox{]} -\/\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} \mbox{[}1, 2, 3\mbox{]} \+: \mbox{[}1, 2, 3\mbox{]} 函数调用图\+:

iota

Requires\+: T shall be convertible to Forward\+Iterator\textquotesingle{}s value type. The expression ++val, where val has type T, shall be well formed. Effects\+: For each element referred to by the iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last), assigns \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i = value and increments value as if by ++value. Complexity\+: Exactly last -\/ first increments and assignments. Example usage\+: seeding a deck of cards with values 0-\/51. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a815c6b5979a970d9b11b39e61b1bbe4a}\index{eastl@{eastl}!is@{is}}

is\+\_\+sorted

Returns true if the range \mbox{[}first, last) is sorted. An empty range is considered to be sorted. To test if a range is reverse-\/sorted, use \textquotesingle{}greater\textquotesingle{} as the comparison instead of \textquotesingle{}less\textquotesingle{}.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} int\+Array; bool b\+Is\+Sorted = is\+\_\+sorted(int\+Array.\+begin(), int\+Array.\+end()); bool b\+Is\+Reverse\+Sorted = is\+\_\+sorted(int\+Array.\+begin(), int\+Array.\+end(), greater$<$int$>$()); \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a736cc3a06a7726c16949c5932e5e9ab9}\index{eastl@{eastl}!is\_sorted\_until@{is\_sorted\_until}}

is\+\_\+sorted\+\_\+until

Returns an iterator to the first element in the range \mbox{[}first,last) which does not follow an ascending order. The range between first and the iterator returned is sorted. If the entire range is sorted, the function returns last. The elements are compared using operator\texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} for the first version, and comp for the second.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} int\+Array; \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector_a4bae2bde2429116a3cb0e31b2168ccbe}{vector$<$int$>$\+::iterator} unsorted\+\_\+element = is\+\_\+sorted\+\_\+until(eastl\+::end(int\+Array), eastl\+::end(int\+Array)); \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector_a4bae2bde2429116a3cb0e31b2168ccbe}{vector$<$int$>$\+::iterator} unsorted\+\_\+element\+\_\+with\+\_\+user\+\_\+compare = is\+\_\+sorted\+\_\+until(eastl\+::end(int\+Array), eastl\+::end(int\+Array), eastl\+::less$<$int$>$()); 函数调用图\+:

iter\+\_\+swap

Swaps the values of the elements the given iterators are pointing to.

Equivalent to swap(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}a, \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}b), though the user can provide an override to iter\+\_\+swap that is independent of an override which may exist for swap.

We provide a version of iter\+\_\+swap which uses swap when the swapped types are equal but a manual implementation otherwise. We do this because the C++ standard defect report says that iter\+\_\+swap(a, b) must be implemented as swap(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}a, \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}b) when possible. 函数调用图\+:

lexicographical\+\_\+compare

Returns\+: true if the sequence of elements defined by the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) is lexicographically less than the sequence of elements defined by the range \mbox{[}first2, last2). Returns false otherwise.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}min((last1 -\/ first1), (last2 -\/ first2))\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding comparison.

Note\+: If two sequences have the same number of elements and their corresponding elements are equivalent, then neither sequence is lexicographically less than the other. If one sequence is a prefix of the other, then the shorter sequence is lexicographically less than the longer sequence. Otherwise, the lexicographical comparison of the sequences yields the same result as the comparison of the first corresponding pair of elements that are not equivalent. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a112139a58693489e9dab3d4521ace76c}\index{eastl@{eastl}!lexicographical\_compare@{lexicographical\_compare}}

lexicographical\+\_\+compare

Returns\+: true if the sequence of elements defined by the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) is lexicographically less than the sequence of elements defined by the range \mbox{[}first2, last2). Returns false otherwise.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}min((last1 -\/first1), (last2 -\/ first2))\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding comparison.

Note\+: If two sequences have the same number of elements and their corresponding elements are equivalent, then neither sequence is lexicographically less than the other. If one sequence is a prefix of the other, then the shorter sequence is lexicographically less than the longer sequence. Otherwise, the lexicographical comparison of the sequences yields the same result as the comparison of the first corresponding pair of elements that are not equivalent.

Note\+: False is always returned if range 1 is exhausted before range 2. The result of this is that you can\textquotesingle{}t do a successful reverse compare (e.\+g. use \doxylink{structeastl_1_1greater}{greater$<$$>$} as the comparison instead of \doxylink{structeastl_1_1less}{less$<$$>$}) unless the two sequences are of identical length. What you want to do is reverse the order of the arguments in order to get the desired effect. 函数调用图\+:

lower\+\_\+bound

Finds the position of the first element in a sorted range that has a value greater than or equivalent to a specified value.

Effects\+: Finds the first position into which value can be inserted without violating the ordering.

Returns\+: The furthermost iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, i) the following corresponding condition holds\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} value.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}log(last -\/ first) + 1\textquotesingle{} comparisons.

Optimizations\+: We have no need to specialize this implementation for random access iterators (e.\+g. contiguous array), as the code below will already take advantage of them. 函数调用图\+:

lower\+\_\+bound

Finds the position of the first element in a sorted range that has a value greater than or equivalent to a specified value. The input Compare function takes two arguments and returns true if the first argument is less than the second argument.

Effects\+: Finds the first position into which value can be inserted without violating the ordering.

Returns\+: The furthermost iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, i) the following corresponding condition holds\+: compare(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j, value) != false.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}log(last -\/ first) + 1\textquotesingle{} comparisons.

Optimizations\+: We have no need to specialize this implementation for random access iterators (e.\+g. contiguous array), as the code below will already take advantage of them. 函数调用图\+:

make\+\_\+pair / make\+\_\+pair\+\_\+ref

make\+\_\+pair is the same as std\+::make\+\_\+pair specified by the C++ standard. If you look at the C++ standard, you\textquotesingle{}ll see that it specifies T\& instead of T. However, it has been determined that the C++ standard is incorrect and has flagged it as a defect (\href{http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/lwg-defects.html\#181}{\texttt{ http\+://www.\+open-\/std.\+org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/lwg-\/defects.\+html\#181}}). In case you feel that you want a more efficient version that uses references, we provide the make\+\_\+pair\+\_\+ref function below, though C++11 move support makes that no longer necessary.

Note\+: You don\textquotesingle{}t usually need to use make\+\_\+pair in order to make a pair. The following code is equivalent, and the latter avoids one more level of inlining\+: return make\+\_\+pair(char\+Ptr, char\+Ptr); return pair$<$char\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}, char\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}$>$(char\+Ptr, char\+Ptr); 函数调用图\+:

make\+\_\+unique

The C++11 Standard doesn\textquotesingle{}t have make\+\_\+unique, but there\textquotesingle{}s no agreed reason as to why. \href{http://stackoverflow.com/questions/12580432/why-does-c11-have-make-shared-but-not-make-unique}{\texttt{ http\+://stackoverflow.\+com/questions/12580432/why-\/does-\/c11-\/have-\/make-\/shared-\/but-\/not-\/make-\/unique}} \href{http://herbsutter.com/2013/05/29/gotw-89-solution-smart-pointers/}{\texttt{ http\+://herbsutter.\+com/2013/05/29/gotw-\/89-\/solution-\/smart-\/pointers/}} Herb\textquotesingle{}s solution is OK but doesn\textquotesingle{}t support \doxylink{classeastl_1_1unique__ptr}{unique\+\_\+ptr$<$\mbox{[}$\,$\mbox{]}$>$} (array version). We do the same thing libc++ does and make a specialization of make\+\_\+unique for arrays.

make\+\_\+unique has two cases where you can\textquotesingle{}t use it and need to directly use \doxylink{classeastl_1_1unique__ptr}{unique\+\_\+ptr}\+:
\begin{DoxyItemize}
\item You need to construct the \doxylink{classeastl_1_1unique__ptr}{unique\+\_\+ptr} with a raw pointer.
\item You need to specify a custom deleter.
\end{DoxyItemize}

Note\+: This function uses global new T by default to create the ptr instance, as per the C++11 Standard make\+\_\+shared\+\_\+ptr.

Example usage\+: struct \doxylink{class_test}{Test}\{ \doxylink{class_test}{Test(int, int)}\{\} \}; auto p = make\+\_\+unique$<$\+Test$>$(1, 2);

auto p\+Array = make\+\_\+unique$<$\+Test\mbox{[}$\,$\mbox{]}$>$(4); 函数调用图\+:

Forward\+Iterator eastl\+::max\+\_\+element (\begin{DoxyParamCaption}\item[{Forward\+Iterator}]{first}{, }\item[{Forward\+Iterator}]{last}{}\end{DoxyParamCaption})}

max\+\_\+element

max\+\_\+element finds the largest element in the range \mbox{[}first, last). It returns the first iterator i in \mbox{[}first, last) such that no other iterator in \mbox{[}first, last) points to a value greater than \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i. The return value is last if and only if \mbox{[}first, last) is an empty range.

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, last) the following corresponding condition holds\+: !(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j).

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}max((last -\/ first) -\/ 1, 0)\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding comparisons. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a50e2ed0c3cb45bf6139246c735d588bf}\index{eastl@{eastl}!max\_element@{max\_element}}

max\+\_\+element

max\+\_\+element finds the largest element in the range \mbox{[}first, last). It returns the first iterator i in \mbox{[}first, last) such that no other iterator in \mbox{[}first, last) points to a value greater than \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i. The return value is last if and only if \mbox{[}first, last) is an empty range.

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, last) the following corresponding condition holds\+: compare(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i, \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j) == false.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}max((last -\/ first) -\/ 1, 0)\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding comparisons. 函数调用图\+:

min\+\_\+element

min\+\_\+element finds the smallest element in the range \mbox{[}first, last). It returns the first iterator i in \mbox{[}first, last) such that no other iterator in \mbox{[}first, last) points to a value smaller than \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i. The return value is last if and only if \mbox{[}first, last) is an empty range.

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, last) the following corresponding condition holds\+: !(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i).

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}max((last -\/ first) -\/ 1, 0)\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding comparisons. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a8400b84ad5f22b011c896eff72a7f4ea}\index{eastl@{eastl}!min\_element@{min\_element}}

mismatch

Finds the first position where the two ranges \mbox{[}first1, last1) and \mbox{[}first2, first2 + (last1 -\/ first1)) differ. The two versions of mismatch use different tests for whether elements differ.

Returns\+: A pair of iterators i and j such that j == first2 + (i -\/ first1) and i is the first iterator in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) for which the following corresponding condition holds\+: !(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i == \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first2 + (i -\/ first1))). Returns the pair last1 and first2 + (last1 -\/ first1) if such an iterator i is not found.

Complexity\+: At most last1 first1 applications of the corresponding predicate. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_aead2793ffad8cf612c7795cdd7152dd1}\index{eastl@{eastl}!mismatch@{mismatch}}

move\+\_\+backward

The elements are moved in reverse order (the last element is moved first), but their relative order is preserved. After this operation the elements in the moved-\/from range will still contain valid values of the appropriate type, but not necessarily the same values as before the move. Returns the beginning of the result range. Note\+: When moving between containers, the dest range must be valid; this function doesn\textquotesingle{}t resize containers. Note\+: If result is within \mbox{[}first, last), move must be used instead of move\+\_\+backward.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{namespaceeastl_abe2a52cd846f3332a63197c957240b1c}{eastl\+::move\+\_\+backward}(my\+Array.\+begin(), my\+Array.\+end(), my\+Dest\+Array.\+end());

Reference implementation\+: template \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}typename Bidirectional\+Iterator1, typename Bidirectional\+Iterator2\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} Bidirectional\+Iterator2 \doxylink{namespaceeastl_abe2a52cd846f3332a63197c957240b1c}{move\+\_\+backward(\+Bidirectional\+Iterator1 first, Bidirectional\+Iterator1 last, Bidirectional\+Iterator2 result\+End)} \{ while(last != first) \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}--result\+End = \doxylink{namespaceeastl_a58ada88d74ffe16bba892a0ccccc8aba}{eastl\+::move}(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}--last); return result\+End; \} 函数调用图\+:

next\+\_\+permutation

mutates the range \mbox{[}first, last) to the next permutation. Returns true if the new range is not the final permutation (sorted like the starting permutation). Permutations start with a sorted range, and false is returned when next\+\_\+permutation results in the initial sorted range, or if the range has \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}= 1 element. Note that elements are compared by operator \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} (as usual) and that elements deemed equal via this are not rearranged.

\href{http://marknelson.us/2002/03/01/next-permutation/}{\texttt{ http\+://marknelson.\+us/2002/03/01/next-\/permutation/}} Basically we start with an ordered range and reverse it\textquotesingle{}s order one specifically chosen swap and reverse at a time. It happens that this require going through every permutation of the range. We use the same variable names as the document above.

To consider\+: Significantly improved permutation/combination functionality\+: \href{http://home.roadrunner.com/~hinnant/combinations.html}{\texttt{ http\+://home.\+roadrunner.\+com/\texorpdfstring{$\sim$}{\string~}hinnant/combinations.\+html}}

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} int\+Array; // $<$populate int\+Array$>$ sort(int\+Array.\+begin(), int\+Array.\+end()); do \{ // $<$do something with int\+Array$>$ \} while(next\+\_\+permutation(int\+Array.\+begin(), int\+Array.\+end())); 函数调用图\+:

operator!= Compares two \doxylink{classeastl_1_1shared__array}{shared\+\_\+array} objects for inequality. Equality is defined as being true when the pointer shared between two \doxylink{classeastl_1_1shared__array}{shared\+\_\+array} objects is equal. It is debatable what the appropriate definition of equality is between two \doxylink{classeastl_1_1shared__array}{shared\+\_\+array} objects, but we follow the current 2nd generation C++ standard proposal. 函数调用图\+:

partial\+\_\+sum

Accumulates the values in the range \mbox{[}first, last) using operator+. As each successive input value is added into the total, that partial sum is written to result. Therefore, the first value in result is the first value of the input, the second value in result is the sum of the first and second input values, and so on. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_ac7d3d2923579f560bd8b8fce552b8b99}\index{eastl@{eastl}!partial\_sum@{partial\_sum}}

template$<$typename Input\+Iterator, typename Predicate$>$ \\
Input\+Iterator eastl\+::partition (\begin{DoxyParamCaption}\item[{Input\+Iterator}]{begin}{, }\item[{Input\+Iterator}]{end}{, }\item[{Predicate}]{predicate}{}\end{DoxyParamCaption})}

partition

Implements the partition algorithm. Rearranges the elements in the range \mbox{[}first, last), in such a way that all the elements for which pred returns true precede all those for which it returns false. The iterator returned points to the first element of the second group. The relative ordering within each group is not necessarily the same as before the call. See function stable\+\_\+partition for a function with a similar behavior and stability in the ordering.

To do\+: Implement a version that uses a faster Bidirectional\+Iterator algorithm for the case that the iterator range is a bidirectional iterator instead of just an input iterator (one direction). 函数调用图\+:

partition\+\_\+point

Precondition\+: for this function to work correctly the input range \mbox{[}first, last) must be partitioned by the predicate. i.\+e. all values for which predicate(v) is true should precede any value in the range for which predicate(v) is false.

Returns\+: the iterator past the end of the first partition within \mbox{[}first, last) or last if all elements satisfy the predicate.

Note\+: this is a more general version of lower\+\_\+bound. 函数调用图\+:

pop\+\_\+heap

Removes the first item from the heap (which is an array), and adjusts the heap so that the highest priority item becomes the new first item.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} heap;

heap.\+push\+\_\+back(2); heap.\+push\+\_\+back(3); heap.\+push\+\_\+back(1); \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}use heap\mbox{[}0\mbox{]}, which is the highest priority item in the heap\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} pop\+\_\+heap(heap.\+begin(), heap.\+end()); // Moves heap\mbox{[}0\mbox{]} to the back of the heap and adjusts the heap. heap.\+pop\+\_\+back(); // Remove value that was just at the top of the heap 函数调用图\+:

push\+\_\+heap

Adds an item to a heap (which is an array). The item necessarily comes from the back of the heap (array). Thus, the insertion of a new item in a heap is a two step process\+: push\+\_\+back and push\+\_\+heap.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} heap;

heap.\+push\+\_\+back(3); push\+\_\+heap(heap.\+begin(), heap.\+end()); // Places \textquotesingle{}3\textquotesingle{} appropriately. 函数调用图\+:

quick\+\_\+sort

This is an unstable sort. quick\+\_\+sort sorts the elements in \mbox{[}first, last) into ascending order, meaning that if i and j are any two valid iterators in \mbox{[}first, last) such that i precedes j, then \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j is not less than \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i. quick\+\_\+sort is not guaranteed to be stable. That is, suppose that \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i and \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j are equivalent\+: neither one is less than the other. It is not guaranteed that the relative order of these two elements will be preserved by sort.

We implement the "{}introspective"{} variation of quick-\/sort. This is considered to be the best general-\/purpose variant, as it avoids worst-\/case behaviour and optimizes the final sorting stage by switching to an insertion sort. 函数调用图\+:

template$<$typename Forward\+Iterator, typename T$>$ \\
Forward\+Iterator eastl\+::remove (\begin{DoxyParamCaption}\item[{Forward\+Iterator}]{first}{, }\item[{Forward\+Iterator}]{last}{, }\item[{const T \&}]{value}{}\end{DoxyParamCaption})\hspace{0.3cm}{\ttfamily [inline]}}

remove

Effects\+: Eliminates all the elements referred to by iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding condition holds\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i == value.

Returns\+: The end of the resulting range.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last -\/ first\textquotesingle{} applications of the corresponding predicate.

Note\+: The predicate version of remove is remove\+\_\+if and not another variation of remove. This is because both versions would have the same parameter count and there could be ambiguity.

Note\+: Since this function moves the element to the back of the heap and doesn\textquotesingle{}t actually remove it from the given container, the user must call the container erase function if the user wants to erase the element from the container.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} int\+Array; ... int\+Array.\+erase(remove(int\+Array.\+begin(), int\+Array.\+end(), 4), int\+Array.\+end()); // Erase all elements of value 4. 函数调用图\+:

remove\+\_\+heap

Removes an arbitrary entry from the heap and adjusts the heap appropriately. This function is unlike pop\+\_\+heap in that pop\+\_\+heap moves the top item to the back of the heap, whereas remove\+\_\+heap moves an arbitrary item to the back of the heap.

Note\+: Since this function moves the element to the back of the heap and doesn\textquotesingle{}t actually remove it from the given container, the user must call the container erase function if the user wants to erase the element from the container. 函数调用图\+:

search

Search finds a subsequence within the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) that is identical to \mbox{[}first2, last2) when compared element-\/by-\/element. It returns an iterator pointing to the beginning of that subsequence, or else last1 if no such subsequence exists. As such, it is very much like the C strstr function, with the primary difference being that strstr uses 0-\/terminated strings whereas search uses an end iterator to specify the end of a string.

Returns\+: The first iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1 -\/ (last2 -\/ first2)) such that for any nonnegative integer n less than \textquotesingle{}last2 -\/ first2\textquotesingle{} the following corresponding condition holds\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(i + n) == \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first2 + n). Returns last1 if no such iterator is found.

Complexity\+: At most (last1 first1) \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} (last2 first2) applications of the corresponding predicate. 函数调用图\+:

set\+\_\+decomposition

set\+\_\+decomposition iterates over both ranges and copies elements to one of the three categories of output ranges.

Effects\+: Constructs three sorted containers of the elements from the two ranges.
\begin{DoxyItemize}
\item Output\+Iterator1 is elements only in Container1.
\item Output\+Iterator2 is elements only in Container2.
\item Output\+Iterator3 is elements that are in both Container1 and Container2.
\end{DoxyItemize}

Requires\+: The input ranges must be sorted. Requires\+: The resulting ranges shall not overlap with either of the original ranges.

Returns\+: The end of the constructed range of elements in both Container1 and Container2.

Complexity\+: At most (2 \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} ((last1 -\/ first1) + (last2 -\/ first2)) -\/ 1) comparisons. 函数调用图\+:

set\+\_\+difference iterates over both input ranges and copies elements present in the first range but not the second to the output range.

Effects\+: Copies the elements of the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) which are not present in the range \mbox{[}first2, last2) to the range beginning at result. The elements in the constructed range are sorted.

Requires\+: The input ranges must be sorted. Requires\+: The output range shall not overlap with either of the original ranges.

Returns\+: The end of the output range.

Complexity\+: At most (2 \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} ((last1 -\/ first1) + (last2 -\/ first2)) -\/ 1) comparisons. 函数调用图\+:

Set\+Assertion\+Failure\+Function

Sets the function called when an assertion fails. If this function is not called by the user, a default function will be used. The user may supply a context parameter which will be passed back to the user in the function call. This is typically used to store a C++ \textquotesingle{}this\textquotesingle{} pointer, though other things are possible.

There is no thread safety here, so the user needs to externally make sure that this function is not called in a thread-\/unsafe way. The easiest way to do this is to just call this function once from the main thread on application startup. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_a2c2e20967fde2549cccbc156438f5e2d}\index{eastl@{eastl}!SetDefaultAllocator@{SetDefaultAllocator}}

shell\+\_\+sort

Implements the Shell\+Sort algorithm. This algorithm is a serious algorithm for larger data sets, as reported by Sedgewick in his discussions on Quick\+Sort. Note that shell\+\_\+sort requires a random access iterator, which usually means an array (eg. vector, deque). Shell\+Sort has good performance with presorted sequences. The term "{}shell"{} derives from the name of the inventor, David Shell.

To consider\+: Allow the user to specify the "{}h-\/sequence"{} array. 函数调用图\+:

shuffle

New for C++11 Randomizes a sequence of values via a user-\/supplied Uniform\+Random\+Number\+Generator. The difference between this and the original random\+\_\+shuffle function is that this uses the more advanced and flexible Uniform\+Random\+Number\+Generator interface as opposed to the more limited Random\+Number\+Generator interface of random\+\_\+shuffle.

Effects\+: Shuffles the elements in the range \mbox{[}first, last) with uniform distribution.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}(last -\/ first) -\/ 1\textquotesingle{} swaps.

Example usage\+: struct Rand\{ \doxylink{config_8h_a2229484fbe7886756129ec4132f03da1}{eastl\+\_\+size\+\_\+t} operator()(eastl\+\_\+size\+\_\+t n) \{ return (\doxylink{config_8h_a2229484fbe7886756129ec4132f03da1}{eastl\+\_\+size\+\_\+t})(rand() \% n); \} \}; // Note\+: The C rand function is poor and slow. Rand rand\+Instance; shuffle(p\+Array\+Begin, p\+Array\+End, rand\+Instance); 函数调用图\+:

sort\+\_\+heap

After the application if this algorithm, the range it was applied to is no longer a heap, though it will be a reverse heap (smallest first). The item with the lowest priority will be first, and the highest last. This is not a stable sort because the relative order of equivalent elements is not necessarily preserved. The range referenced must be valid; all pointers must be dereferenceable and within the sequence the last position is reachable from the first by incrementation. The complexity is at most O(n \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} log(n)), where n is count of the range. 函数调用图\+:

stable\+\_\+sort

We use merge\+\_\+sort by default. See merge\+\_\+sort for details. Beware that the used merge\+\_\+sort -- and thus stable\+\_\+sort -- allocates memory during execution. Try using merge\+\_\+sort\+\_\+buffer if you want to avoid memory allocation.

EASTL\+\_\+\+DEFAULT\+\_\+\+STABLE\+\_\+\+SORT\+\_\+\+FUNCTION If a default sort function is specified then call it, otherwise use EASTL\textquotesingle{}s default merge\+\_\+sort. EASTL\+\_\+\+DEFAULT\+\_\+\+STABLE\+\_\+\+SORT\+\_\+\+FUNCTION must be namespace-\/qualified and include any necessary template parameters (e.\+g. eastl\+::tim\+\_\+sort instead of just tim\+\_\+sort), and it must be visible to this code. The EASTL\+\_\+\+DEFAULT\+\_\+\+STABLE\+\_\+\+SORT\+\_\+\+FUNCTION must be provided in three versions, though the third allocation implementation may choose to ignore the allocator parameter\+: template \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}typename Random\+Access\+Iterator, typename Strict\+Weak\+Ordering\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} void EASTL\+\_\+\+DEFAULT\+\_\+\+STABLE\+\_\+\+SORT\+\_\+\+FUNCTION(\+Random\+Access\+Iterator first, Random\+Access\+Iterator last, Strict\+Weak\+Ordering compare);

swap

Assigns the contents of a to b and the contents of b to a. A temporary instance of type T is created and destroyed in the process.

This function is used by numerous other algorithms, and as such it may in some cases be feasible and useful for the user to implement an override version of this function which is more efficient in some way. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_aa223c346c706c6c0ace60bf60e8ae24d}\index{eastl@{eastl}!swap@{swap}}

swap\+\_\+ranges

Swaps each of the elements in the range \mbox{[}first1, last1) with the corresponding element in the range \mbox{[}first2, first2 + (last1 -\/ first1)).

Effects\+: For each nonnegative integer n \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} (last1 -\/ first1), performs\+: swap(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first1 + n), \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first2 + n)).

Requires\+: The two ranges \mbox{[}first1, last1) and \mbox{[}first2, first2 + (last1 -\/ first1)) shall not overlap.

Returns\+: first2 + (last1 -\/ first1). That is, returns the end of the second range.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last1 -\/ first1\textquotesingle{} swaps. 函数调用图\+:

transform

Iterates the input range of \mbox{[}first, last) and the output iterator result and assigns the result of unary\+Operation(input) to result.

Effects\+: Assigns through every iterator i in the range \mbox{[}result, result + (last1 -\/ first1)) a new corresponding value equal to unary\+Operation(\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(first1 + (i -\/ result)).

Requires\+: op shall not have any side effects.

Returns\+: result + (last1 -\/ first1). That is, returns the end of the output range.

Complexity\+: Exactly \textquotesingle{}last1 -\/ first1\textquotesingle{} applications of unary\+Operation.

Note\+: result may be equal to first. \Hypertarget{namespaceeastl_ab36b8ecbb35b317c87b466e74c9a0848}\index{eastl@{eastl}!transform@{transform}}

uninitialized\+\_\+copy

Copies a source range to a destination, copy-\/constructing the destination with the source values (and not {\itshape assigning} the destination with the source values). Returns the end of the destination range (i.\+e. dest + (last -\/ first)).

Declaration\+: template \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}typename Input\+Iterator, typename Forward\+Iterator\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} Forward\+Iterator \doxylink{namespaceeastl_a8fbae45eba1ae51d58a8f1e701287e7e}{uninitialized\+\_\+copy(\+Input\+Iterator source\+First, Input\+Iterator source\+Last, Forward\+Iterator destination)};

Example usage\+: Some\+Class\texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} p\+Array = \doxylink{mimalloc-override_8h_a99aa8fd9f4831e1b0fa9e1cdcde3e249}{malloc(10 \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} sizeof(\+Some\+Class))}; uninitialized\+\_\+copy(p\+Source\+Data\+Begin, p\+Source\+Data\+Begin + 10, p\+Array); 函数调用图\+:

Moves a source range to a destination, move-\/constructing the destination with the source values (and not {\itshape assigning} the destination with the source values). Returns the end of the destination range (i.\+e. dest + (last -\/ first)).

unique

Given a sorted range, this function removes duplicated items. Note that if you have a container then you will probably want to call erase on the container with the return value if your goal is to remove the duplicated items from the container.

Effects\+: Eliminates all but the first element from every consecutive group of equal elements referred to by the iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) for which the following corresponding condition holds\+: \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}i == \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}(i -\/ 1).

Returns\+: The end of the resulting range.

Complexity\+: If the range (last -\/ first) is not empty, exactly (last -\/ first) applications of the corresponding predicate, otherwise no applications of the predicate.

Example usage\+: \doxylink{classeastl_1_1vector}{vector$<$int$>$} int\+Array; ... int\+Array.\+erase(unique(int\+Array.\+begin(), int\+Array.\+end()), int\+Array.\+end()); 函数调用图\+:

upper\+\_\+bound

Finds the position of the first element in a sorted range that has a value that is greater than a specified value.

Effects\+: Finds the furthermost position into which value can be inserted without violating the ordering.

Returns\+: The furthermost iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, i) the following corresponding condition holds\+: !(value \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j).

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}log(last -\/ first) + 1\textquotesingle{} comparisons. 函数调用图\+:

upper\+\_\+bound

Finds the position of the first element in a sorted range that has a value that is greater than a specified value. The input Compare function takes two arguments and returns true if the first argument is less than the second argument.

Effects\+: Finds the furthermost position into which value can be inserted without violating the ordering.

Returns\+: The furthermost iterator i in the range \mbox{[}first, last) such that for any iterator j in the range \mbox{[}first, i) the following corresponding condition holds\+: compare(value, \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}j) == false.

Complexity\+: At most \textquotesingle{}log(last -\/ first) + 1\textquotesingle{} comparisons. 函数调用图\+:

invoke

invoke is a generalized function-\/call operator which works on function pointers, member function pointers, callable objects and member pointers.

For (member/non-\/member) function pointers and callable objects, it returns the result of calling the function/object with the specified arguments. For member data pointers, it simply returns the member.

Note that there are also \doxylink{classeastl_1_1reference__wrapper}{reference\+\_\+wrapper} specializations of invoke, which need to be defined later since \doxylink{classeastl_1_1reference__wrapper}{reference\+\_\+wrapper} uses invoke in its implementation. Those are defined immediately after the definition of \doxylink{classeastl_1_1reference__wrapper}{reference\+\_\+wrapper}.
